    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Calopsis andreaeana are tincture, infusion, calopsis tea, salve, and decoction. A tincture is made by soaking the plant in a solvent, typically ethanol or glycerin, to extract its bioactive compounds. An infusion is prepared by steeping the plant in hot water to release its volatile oils and flavonoids, while calopsis tea is a more concentrated form of infusion. A salve is created by mixing the plant's extracts with a carrier oil, such as coconut or olive oil, to produce a topical remedy for skin issues. A decoction, on the other hand, involves boiling the plant's roots or bark to extract its alkaloids and other non-volatile compounds.",
